Now that we have the given values, we can solve for the retention ratio. This refers to the percentage of the earnings that are retained and reinvested in the company. To do this, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention ratio}&=1-\dfrac{\left(\frac{\text{Dividend}}{\text{Number of shares}}\right)}{\text{Earnings per share}}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention ratio}&=1-\dfrac{\left(\frac{\$45,000}{50,000}\right)}{\$3.15}\\[15 pt]
&=0.7143
\end{aligned}$$

The retention rate is $0.7143$ or $71.43\%$.

Now that we have the retention rate, we can solve for the appropriate growth rate using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Growth rate}&=\text{Retention rate} \times \text{Return on retentions}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Growth rate}&=0.7143 \times 0.17\\[15 pt]
&=0.1214
\end{aligned}$$

The growth rate of the company is $0.1214$ or $12.14\%$.

Finally, we can solve for the appropriate price of the company's stock using this equation:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Price of company's stock}&=\dfrac{\frac{\text{Current dividend}}{\text{Number of shares}}\times(1+\text{Growth rate})}{(\text{Cost of common equity}-\text{Growth rate})}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Price of company's stock}&=\dfrac{\frac{\$45,000}{50,000} \times (1+0.1214)}{(0.14-0.1214)}\\[15 pt]
&=\$54.26
\end{aligned}$$

The company's stock should be $\$54.26$.
